author: BBC News
description:
In Israel memorial events have been taking place on the second anniversary of the October 7 attacks by Hamas.  Some 1,200 people were killed that day and 251 were taken hostage.  

In response Israel launched its military campaign in Gaza, where more than 67,000 people have been killed according to the Hamas-run health ministry.

Indirect talks have been continuing in Egypt between Israel and the Palestinians to try to agree US President Trump’s plans to end the war.

Fiona Bruce presents BBC News at Ten reporting by Lucy Williamson and Jeremy Bowen.

title: Israel mourns October 7 victims as Trump’s peace plan talks continue | BBC News

author: BBC News
description:
Today, how much political danger are the Conservative party in?

Adam and Chris are at Conservative party conference in Manchester where some comments from shadow justice secretary Robert Jenrick have dominated the headlines.

In a recording reportedly made during a dinner and published by the Guardian, Jenrick said he had not seen "another white face" in the hour-and-a-half he spent in the Handsworth area of Birmingham filming a video about litter. Jenrick has defended the comments. Adam and Chris discuss this and the general state of the Conservative party.

Adam is also joined by James Cleverly the shadow housing secretary.

author: BBC News
description:
The Nobel Prize in Physics has been awarded to John Clarke, Michel H. Devoret and John M. Martinis for their work on quantum mechanics that is paving the way for a new generation of very powerful computers.
 
"There is no advanced technology used today that does not rely on quantum mechanics, including mobile phones, cameras... and fibre optic cables," said the Nobel committee.
 
The announcement was made by the Royal Swedish Academy of Sciences at a news conference in Stockholm, Sweden.
 
The three winners will share prize money of 11 million Swedish kronor (£872,000).

author: BBC News
description:
Renewable energy overtook coal as the world's leading source of electricity in the first half of this year - a historic first, according to new data from the global energy think tank Ember.

Electricity demand has grown around the world but the growth in solar and wind was so strong it met 100% of the extra electricity demand.

However, Ember said the headlines mask a mixed global picture.

Developing countries, especially China, led the clean energy charge but richer nations including the US and EU relied more than before on planet-warming fossil fuels for electricity generation.

author: BBC News
description:
Police said they have dismantled an international gang suspected of smuggling up to 40,000 stolen mobile phones from the UK to China in the past year.

In what the Metropolitan Police said is the UK's largest ever operation against phone thefts, 18 suspects have been arrested and more than 2,000 stolen devices discovered.

Police believe the gang could be responsible for exporting up to half of all phones stolen in London, where most mobiles are taken in the UK.

BBC News has been given access to the operation, including details of the suspects, their methods, and to raids on 28 properties in London and Hertfordshire.

title: Police bust gang suspected of sending up to 40,000 stolen UK phones to China | BBC News

author: BBC News
description:
Israelis have gathered at memorial events to mark two years since Hamas's attacks on 7 October 2023, in which about 1,200 people were killed and 251 others were taken hostage.
 
At the site of the Nova festival attack, memorials have been garnished with flowers, tributes and candles. 
 
The sister-in-law of one of 20 hostages believed to be alive in Gaza said she and other families will "keep fighting" until they are all returned to Israel.
 
Israel's military launched a campaign in Gaza in response to Hamas's attacks, which has killed at least 67,160 people there, according to the Hamas-run health ministry.
